Document: Creating a 3D Particle System  
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/particles/creating_a_3d_particle_system.rst  
Summary: Adding a GPUParticles3D node and configuring its Process Material and Draw Pass parameters to create a 3D particle system.  

To get started with particles, the first thing we need to do is add a GPUParticles3D node to the scene. Before we can actually see any particles, we have to set up two parameters on the node: the Process Material and at least one Draw Pass.
---CHUNK---
Document: Creating a 3D Particle System  
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/particles/creating_a_3d_particle_system.rst  
Summary: How to add and configure a ParticleProcessMaterial for GPU-based particle behavior in Godot  

To add a process material to your particles node, go to Process Material in the inspector panel. Click on the box next to Process Material and from the dropdown menu select New ParticleProcessMaterial. ParticleProcessMaterial is a special kind of material. We don't use it to draw any objects. We use it to update particle data and behavior on the GPU instead of the CPU, which comes with a massive performance boost. A click on the newly added material displays a long list of properties that you can set to control each particle's behavior.
---CHUNK---
Document: Creating a 3D Particle System  
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/particles/creating_a_3d_particle_system.rst  
Summary: Explains how to configure draw passes for rendering particles in a 3D particle system.  

To render particles, at least one draw pass must be defined. In the inspector panel, navigate to "Draw Passes" and select "New QuadMesh" for Pass 1. Set the mesh's "Size" to 0.1 for both x and y axes to distinguish individual particles. Up to four draw passes can be used per particle system, each with a unique mesh and material. All passes use data computed by the process material, enabling efficient rendering of complex effects by calculating particle behavior once and reusing it across multiple passes.  

Multiple draw passes allow distinct visual elements. For example, one pass might render yellow rectangles while another renders blue spheres. After configuring the passes, the particle system will emit particles in a waterfall-like motion, moving downward and disappearing after a few seconds. This forms the foundation for all particle effects. For advanced customization, refer to the documentation for "particle" and "particle material" properties to explore additional parameters and techniques.
---CHUNK---
Document: Creating a 3D Particle System
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/particles/creating_a_3d_particle_system.rst
Summary: Converting between GPU and CPU particle systems and their feature limitations

Particle conversion

You can convert GPU particles to CPU particles at any time using the entry in the viewport menu. When you do so, keep in mind that not every feature of GPU particles is available for CPU particles, so the resulting particle system will look and behave differently from the original. Note: Multiple draw passes, turbulence, sub-emitters, trails, attractors, and collision features are lost during conversion.

You can also convert CPU particles to GPU particles if you no longer need to use CPU particles. This is also done from the viewport menu.

Key Rule: Converting GPU to CPU particles removes the following properties: Amount Ratio, Interp to End, Damping as Friction, Emission Shape Offset, Emission Shape Scale, Inherit Velocity Ratio, Velocity Pivot, Directional Velocity, Radial Velocity, Velocity Limit, and Scale Over Velocity.

Converting GPU particles to CPU particles can become necessary when you want to release a game on older devices that don't support modern graphics APIs.